 occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Anne Plantagenet Cockerell was born in 1542, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Cockrill, was 22 and her mother, Lady Eleanor Smith Porter, was 22. She married John Plantagenet on 5 November 1557. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1576, in Bishopsgate, London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1542–1576":"1542–1576","1540–1585":"1540–1585","1540–Male":"1540–Surnud","1545–1625":"1545–1625","1540–1631":"1540–1631","1556–1643":"1556–1643","1520–1576":"1520–1576","1520–1546":"1520–1546","1546":"1546","1556":"1556","5 November 1557":"5. november 1557","1545":"1545","1643":"1643","1576":"1576","1631":"1631","1542":"1542","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1625":"1625","England":"England","Welton, Oxfordshire, , England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Botolph, Bishopsgate, London, England":"Bishopsgate, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Newport Pagnell, Buckinghamshire, England":"Newport Pagnell, Buckinghamshire, England"},"